1 (1) solely due to the sexual orientation or gender identity of the individual
2 being discharged; [or]
3 (2) based on a statement or consensual act of the individual being
4 discharged related to the individual’s sexual orientation or gender identity, if the statement
5 or consensual act was prohibited by the military or naval service at the time of discharge;
6 OR
7 (3) BASED ON AN INCIDENT OR INCIDENTS RELATING TO:
8 (I) A DIAGNOSIS OF POST–TRAUMATIC STRESS DISORDER OR
9 TRAUMATIC BRAIN INJURY MADE BY AN INDIVIDUAL LICENSED TO PROVIDE HEALTH
10 CARE SERVICES AT A U.S. DEPARTMENT OF VETERANS AFFAIRS FACILITY; OR
11 (II) AN EXPERIENCE OF SEXUAL TRAUMA, AS DESCRIBED IN 38
12 U.S.C. § 1720, DISCLOSED TO AN INDIVIDUAL LICENSED TO PROVIDE HEALTH CARE
13 SERVICES AT A U.S. DEPARTMENT OF VETERANS AFFAIRS FACILITY.
14 (3) IF THE DEPARTMENT OF VETERANS AND MILITARY FAMILIES
15 DETERMINES AN INDIVIDUAL IS ELIGIBLE FOR STATE BENEFITS BASED ON THE
16 CRITERIA ESTABLISHED IN 38 C.F.R. § 3.12.
17 (b) A veteran shall submit to the Secretary of Veterans and Military Families
18 documentation that provides the basis for the veteran’s discharge.
19 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect
20 October 1, 2025.
